# Git commit summary (required)

After finishing a task that changes files, **always** end with a ready-to-paste git commit summary — even if the user has not asked to commit yet, and even if they commit themselves.

## Format

Use conventional commits (`feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`):

```text
<type>(optional-scope): <imperative summary, ~50–72 chars>

Optional 1–3 sentence body: why + notable behavior, not a file list.
```

## Rules

- Focus on **why** / user-facing outcome, not every file touched.
- One logical change → one message. If the session mixed unrelated work, give **separate** summaries per concern.
- Do not invent issue numbers unless the user referenced one (`#123`).
- If you also create the commit (only when the user asks), use this same message via HEREDOC — do not skip the summary in chat.
- If the working tree is already committed by the user with a vague message, still offer the improved summary they can use next time (or for amend only if they explicitly ask).

## Example

```text
feat(files): add sortable columns and drag-and-drop upload

List headers sort filtered files; dropping a file opens the upload
dialog with it preselected. Removes unused uploader filter chrome.
```
